\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Ehrenfest
\end_layout

\end_inset

For electron–radiation dynamics, the most natural approach is the Ehrenfest
 method, combining the quantum Liouville equation with classical electrodynamics
 in a mean-field manner; this approach should be reliable given the lack
 of a time-scale separation between electronic and EM dynamics.
 Nevertheless, Ehrenfest dynamics are known to suffer from several drawbacks.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
detail balance
\end_layout

\end_inset

First, it is well-known that, for electronic–nuclear dynamics, Ehrenfest
 dynamics do not satisfy detailed balance.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "parandekar_detailed_2006"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 This drawback will usually lead to incorrect electronic populations at
 long times.
 The failure to maintain detailed balance results in anomalous energy flow
 (that can even sometimes violate the second law of thermodynamics at equilibriu
m.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "jain_vibrational_2018"
literal "true"

\end_inset

) For electron–radiation dynamics, this problem may not be fatal since the
 absorption and emission of a radiation field may be considered relatively
 fast compared to electronic–nuclear dynamics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
partially correct
\end_layout

\end_inset

Apart from any concerns about detail balance, Ehrenfest dynamics has a second
 deficiency related to spontaneous and stimulated emission.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "li_mixed_2018"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 Consider a situation where the electronic system has zero average current
 initially and exists within a vacuum environment without external fields;
 if the electronic state is excited, one expects spontaneous emission to
 occur.
 However, according to Ehrenfest dynamics, the electron–radiation coupling
 will remain zero always, so that Ehrenfest dynamics will not predict any
 spontaneous emission.
 
