Spontaneous emission is an irreversible process whereby a quantum system
 makes a transition from an excited state to the ground state, while simultaneou
sly emitting a photon into the vacuum.
 The general consensus is that spontaneous emission cannot fully be described
 by any classical electromagnetic theory; almost by definition, a complete
 description of spontaneous emission requires quantization of the photon
 field.
 In this section, we review the Weisskopf–Wigner theory
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "weisskopf_berechnung_1930,scully_quantum_1997"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 of spontaneous emission, evaluating both the expectation value of the electric
 field and the emission intensity.
