\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
PZW Hamiltonian
\end_layout

\end_inset

Before studying spontaneous emission in detail, one must choose a Hamiltonian
 and a gauge for QED calculations.
 We will work with the Power-Zienau-Woolley (PZW) Hamiltonian
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "power_coulomb_1959,atkins_interaction_1970,cohen-tannoudji_photons_1997"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 in the Coulomb gauge (so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}_{\parallel}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}=\mathbf{A}_{\perp}$
\end_inset

) because we believe this combination naturally offers a semiclassical interpret
ation.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "cohen-tannoudji_photons_1997"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 Here, the total Hamiltonian is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{H}_{\text{PZW}}=\widehat{H}_{P}+\widehat{H}_{R}+\widehat{H}_{I},\label{eq:Power-Zienau-Woolley}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the particle Hamiltonian is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{H}_{P}=\widehat{H}_{s}+\frac{1}{2\epsilon_{0}}\int\mathrm{d}v\left|\widehat{\mathbf{P}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)\right|^{2},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

the transverse radiation field Hamiltonian is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{H}_{R}=\int\mathrm{d}v\left\{ \frac{1}{2\epsilon_{0}}\widehat{\mathbf{D}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)^{2}+\frac{1}{2\mu_{0}}\left(\mathbf{\boldsymbol{\nabla}}\times\widehat{\mathbf{A}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)\right)^{2}\right\} ,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the light-matter interaction is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{H}_{I}=-\frac{1}{\epsilon_{0}}\int\mathrm{d}v\widehat{\mathbf{D}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)\cdot\widehat{\mathbf{P}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right).\label{eq:PZW_int}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{H}_{\text{int}}=-\frac{1}{\epsilon_{0}}\int\mathrm{d}\mathbf{r}\widehat{\mathbf{D}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)\cdot\widehat{\mathbf{P}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{A}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the vector potential of the EM field and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{D}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the transverse field displacement, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{D}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)=-\frac{\epsilon_{0}}{c}\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\widehat{\mathbf{A}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)+\widehat{\mathbf{P}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the displacement 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{D}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the momentum conjugate to the vector potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{A}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

, satisfying the canonical commutation relation, 
\begin_inset Formula $[\widehat{\mathbf{D}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right),\widehat{\mathbf{A}}\left(\mathbf{r}^{\prime}\right)]=i\hbar\delta^{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}-\mathbf{r}^{\prime}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We denote the polarization operator of the subsystem as 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{P}}$
\end_inset

 and use the Helmholtz decomposition expression (
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{P}}=\widehat{\mathbf{P}}_{\perp}+\widehat{\mathbf{P}}_{\parallel}$
\end_inset

) to separate the the transverse polarization (satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\nabla}\cdot\widehat{\mathbf{P}}_{\perp}=0$
\end_inset

) and the longitudinal polarization (satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\nabla}\times\widehat{\mathbf{P}}_{\parallel}=0$
\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{H}_{s}$
\end_inset

 is the Hamiltonian of the matter system and will be specified below.
 Note that the Power-Zienau-Woolley Hamiltonian is rigorously equivalent
 to the more standard Coulomb (
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{P}}\cdot\widehat{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

) representation of QED, but the matter field is now conveniently decomposed
 into a multipolar form.
 That being said, in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Power-Zienau-Woolley"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 we have ignored all magnetic couplings and an infinite Coulomb self energy;
 we are also assuming we may ignore any relativistic dynamics of the matter
 field.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
transverse
\end_layout

\end_inset

We assume the polarization operator of the matter only has transverse contributi
on to the EM field, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{P}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)=\widehat{\mathbf{P}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 And we consider a globally neutral system, so that the displacement is
 only a transverse field, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{D}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)=\widehat{\mathbf{D}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

, and we will drop the 
\begin_inset Formula $\perp$
\end_inset

 notation.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A, D in second quantization
\end_layout

\end_inset

For QED in the Coulomb gauge, we choose the vector potential and the displacemen
t following the standard canonical quantization approach:
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "cohen-tannoudji_photons_1997"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\mathbf{A}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)=i\sum_{\mathbf{k}}\frac{{\cal E}_{\mathbf{k}}}{\omega_{\mathbf{k}}}\mathbf{e}_{\mathbf{k}}\left(\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}e^{i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{r}}+\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}e^{-i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{r}}\right),\label{eq:A-operator}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\mathbf{D}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)=i\epsilon_{0}\sum_{\mathbf{k}}{\cal E}_{\mathbf{k}}\mathbf{e}_{\mathbf{k}}\left(\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}e^{i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{r}}-\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}e^{-i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{r}}\right).\label{eq:D_operator}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here, the matrix element 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal E}_{\mathbf{k}}=\sqrt{\frac{\hbar\omega_{\mathbf{k}}}{2\epsilon_{0}L^{n}}}$
\end_inset

 is associated with the frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\mathbf{k}}=c\left|\mathbf{k}\right|$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{n}$
\end_inset

 is the volume of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional space.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 are the destruction and creation operators of the photon field and satisfy
 the commutation relations: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}},\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k^{\prime}}}^{\dagger}\right]=\delta\left(\mathbf{k}-\mathbf{k^{\prime}}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

, the transverse Hamiltonian of the EM field can be represented equivalently
 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{H}_{R}=\sum_{\mathbf{k}}\hbar\omega_{\mathbf{k}}\left(\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}+\frac{1}{2}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{D}}_{\perp}$
\end_inset

 are pure EM field operators in the PZW representation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For the same mathematical operator, the physical meaning depends in representati
on.
\end_layout

\end_inset

Finally, within the Coulomb gauge, the electric and magnetic fields can
 be obtained from the vector potential:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\widehat{\mathbf{B}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right) & = & \mathbf{\boldsymbol{\nabla}}\times\widehat{\mathbf{A}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right),\\
\widehat{\mathbf{E}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right) & = & -\frac{1}{c}\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\widehat{\mathbf{A}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)=-\frac{i}{\hbar c}\left[\widehat{H}_{R}+\widehat{H}_{I},\widehat{\mathbf{A}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)\right],
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

recalling that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\boldsymbol{\nabla}}\cdot\widehat{\mathbf{A}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 in the Coulomb gauge.
 The transverse electric field is related to the displacement and the polarizati
on by 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{0}\widehat{\mathbf{E}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)=\widehat{\mathbf{D}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)-\widehat{\mathbf{P}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, these physical observables can also be expressed in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\mathbf{B}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)=i\sum_{\mathbf{k}}{\cal E}_{\mathbf{k}}\frac{\mathbf{k}\times\mathbf{e}_{\mathbf{k}}}{c}\left(\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}e^{i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{r}}-\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}e^{-i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{r}}\right),\label{eq:B_operator}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\mathbf{E}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)=i\sum_{\mathbf{k}}{\cal E}_{\mathbf{k}}\mathbf{e}_{\mathbf{k}}\left(\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}e^{i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{r}}-\widehat{a}_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger}e^{-i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{r}}\right)-\frac{1}{\epsilon_{0}}\widehat{\mathbf{P}}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r}\right).\label{eq:E_operator}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here, we note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{E}}_{\perp}$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not
\emph default
