\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Ehrenfest ansatz
\end_layout

\end_inset

Within Ehrenfest dynamics, the electronic system is described by the electronic
 density matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\rho}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 while the EM field, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)$
\end_inset

, are propagated by classical electrodynamics.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
density matrix - Liouville
\end_layout

\end_inset

The electronic density matrix evolves according to the Liouville equation,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\widehat{\rho}\left(t\right)=-\frac{i}{\hbar}\left[\widehat{H}_{\mathrm{SC}},\widehat{\rho}\left(t\right)\right],\label{eq:liouville_rho}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{H}_{\mathrm{SC}}=\widehat{H}_{\mathrm{SC}}\left(\mathbf{E},\mathbf{B}\right)$
\end_inset

 is a semiclassical Hamiltonian for the quantum subsystem which depends
 only parametrically on the EM fields.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
EM field - Maxwell
\end_layout

\end_inset

The EM field is governed by Maxwell's equations for classical electrodynamics
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\mathbf{B}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right) & = & -\boldsymbol{\nabla}\times\mathbf{E}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right),\label{eq:maxwell_BE}\\
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\mathbf{E}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right) & = & c^{2}\boldsymbol{\nabla}\times\mathbf{B}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)-\frac{1}{\epsilon_{0}}\mathbf{J}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right),\label{eq:maxwell_EB}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the average current is generated by the average polarization of the
 electronic system
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{J}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)=\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\text{Tr}_{s}\left\{ \widehat{\rho}\left(t\right)\widehat{\mathbf{P}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)\right\} \equiv\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\mathbf{P}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right).\label{eq:polarization_mean}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here we define the average polarization (without hat) 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{P}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)=\text{Tr}_{s}\left\{ \widehat{\rho}\left(t\right)\widehat{\mathbf{P}}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Note that Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:maxwell_EB"

\end_inset

 suggests that the longitudinal component of the classical electric field
 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{E}_{\parallel}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)=-\frac{1}{\epsilon_{0}}\mathbf{P}_{\parallel}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right),\label{eq:maxwell_EB_para}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the transverse component satisfies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\mathbf{E}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)=c^{2}\boldsymbol{\nabla}\times\mathbf{B}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)-\frac{1}{\epsilon_{0}}\mathbf{J}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)\label{eq:maxwell_EB_perp}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{J}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)=\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\mathbf{P}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
energy conservation
\end_layout

\end_inset

The total energy of the electronic system and the classical EM field is
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{split}U_{\mathrm{tot}}\left(\widehat{\rho},\mathbf{E},\mathbf{B}\right) & =\mathrm{Tr}_{s}\left(\widehat{\rho}\left(t\right)\widehat{H}_{s}\right)+\\
 & \int\mathrm{d}v\left(\frac{\epsilon_{0}}{2}\mathbf{E}_{\perp}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)^{2}+\frac{1}{2\mu_{0}}\mathbf{B}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)^{2}\right).
\end{split}
\label{eq:total_energy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:total_energy"

\end_inset

, we have replaced all quantum mechanical operators for the EM field by
 their classical expectation values, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\nabla}\times\widehat{\mathbf{A}}\rightarrow\mathbf{B}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathbf{D}}\rightarrow\mathbf{D}_{\perp}=\epsilon_{0}\mathbf{E}_{\perp}+\mathbf{P}_{\perp}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{P}_{\perp}=\text{Tr}_{s}\left\{ \widehat{\rho}\widehat{\mathbf{P}}_{\perp}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 One of the most important strengths of Ehrenfest dynamics is that the total
 energy (
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\mathrm{tot}}$
\end_inset

) is conserved (as can be shown easily).
 Altogether, Ehrenfest dynamics is a self-consistent, computationally inexpensiv
e approach for propagating the electronic states and EM field dynamics simultane
ously.
